##Introduction An example for analyzing the amplicon sequencing data

Data sources: 2017_Dongshan_Sand_Microbiome_16S amplicon sequencing dataset

Copyright: Dr. Anyi Hu (ayhu@iue.ac.cn)

Citation: Anyi Hu*, Hongjie Wang, Meixian Cao, Azhar Rashid, Mingfeng Li, Chang-Ping Yu. Environmental filtering drives the assembly of habitat generalists and specialists in the coastal sand microbial communities of southern China. Microorganisms. Under review ##

Some References for make the R codes below:

  1. Schmidt, M.L., White, J.D. and Denef, V.J. (2016) Phylogenetic conservation of freshwater lake habitat preference varies between abundant bacterioplankton phyla. Environ. Microbiol. 18(4), 1212-1226.

  2. Burns, A.R., Stephens, W.Z., Stagaman, K., Wong, S., Rawls, J.F., Guillemin, K. and Bohannan, B.J. (2016) Contribution of neutral processes to the assembly of gut microbial communities in the zebrafish over host development. ISME J. 10(3), 655-664.

  3. Tucker, C.M., Shoemaker, L.G., Davies, K.F., Nemergut, D.R. and Melbourne, B.A. (2016) Differentiating between niche and neutral assembly in metacommunities using null models of β-diversity. Oikos 125(6), 778-789.

  4. Wu, W., Logares, R., Huang, B. and Hsieh, C.H. (2017) Abundant and rare picoeukaryotic sub-communities present contrasting patterns in the epipelagic waters of marginal seas in the northwestern Pacific Ocean. Environ. Microbiol. 19(1), 287-300.

  5. Sokol, E.R., Herbold, C.W., Lee, C.K., Cary, S.C. and Barrett, J.E. (2013) Local and regional influences over soil microbial metacommunities in the Transantarctic Mountains. Ecosphere 4(11), art136.

  6. Hou, L.; Hu, A.; Chen, S.; Zhang, K.; Orlic, S.; Rashid, A.; Yu, C.P. Deciphering the Assembly Processes of the Key Ecological Assemblages of Microbial Communities in Thirteen Full-Scale Wastewater Treatment Plants. Microbes. Environ. 2019, 34, 169-179.

Analyses and Plots

Fig.2

##########################################################################################################
###PCA analysis of Environmental variables--------------Fig.2
##########################################################################################################
sand2017_env = as(sample_data(dongshan_sand.nonsing), "data.frame")
sand2017_env1 = sand2017_env[,c(9:16,18,20,21,23,24)]

sand2017_env2 <- data.frame(sapply(sand2017_env1, function(x) as.numeric(as.character(x))))
rownames(sand2017_env2) = row.names(sand2017_env)

##
pca_env = rda(sand2017_env2, scale = TRUE, na.action = na.exclude)
plot(pca_env, type = "t")

##Extract PCA scores
data.scores <- as.data.frame(scores(pca_env, choices = 1:2)$sites)  #Using the scores function from vegan to extract the site scores and tranform into data.frame
data.scores$site1 <- sand2017_env$Site1  # create a column of site names, from the rownames of data.scores
data.scores$site <- sand2017_env$Site
data.scores$Environment <- sand2017_env$Environment  
head(data.scores)  #look at the data
##                   PC1        PC2 site1 site      Environment
## DS2017j11j  0.5112976 -0.4353508 JL1_i  JL1 intertidal sands
## DS2017j11s -0.6779364  1.0353260 JL1_b  JL1  backshore sands
## DS2017j12j  0.6826045 -1.5039506 JL1_i  JL1 intertidal sands
## DS2017j12s -0.1670419  0.4915866 JL1_b  JL1  backshore sands
## DS2017j13j  0.8527856  0.5778940 JL1_i  JL1 intertidal sands
## DS2017j13s -0.4861885  0.2159650 JL1_b  JL1  backshore sands
species.scores <- as.data.frame(scores(pca_env, choices = 1:2)$species)  #Using the scores function from vegan to extract the species scores and convert to a data.frame
species.scores$species <- rownames(species.scores)  # create a column of species, from the rownames of species.scores
head(species.scores)  #look at the data
##                   PC1         PC2    species
## Grain.size -0.2175317 -0.80720958 Grain.size
## EC          0.9805036  0.08416332         EC
## TN         -0.3419536 -0.73696160         TN
## NH4.N      -0.1943267  0.75673286      NH4.N
## NO2.N      -0.7869320  0.26003308      NO2.N
## NO3.N       0.2272992  0.45389641      NO3.N
##Define the arrow aesthetic mapping
pca_arrow_map <- aes(xend = PC1, yend = PC2, x = 0, y = 0, 
                     shape = NULL, color = NULL, 
                     label = species)

pca_label_map <- aes(x = 1.1 * PC1, y = 1.1 * PC2, 
                     shape = NULL, color = NULL, 
                     label = species)

pca_arrowhead = arrow(length = unit(0.015, "npc"))

##Plot
pca_plot = plot_ordination(physeq = dongshan_sand.nonsing, ordination = pca_env, 
                           color = "Site", axes = c(1,2)) + 
  aes(color = Site, shape = Environment) + 
  geom_point(aes(colour = Site), alpha = 1, size = 5) + 
  geom_point(colour = "white", size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(name = "Site", values = c("#1919ff","red", "#4daf4a", "#ffae19", 
                                               "#a65628", "darkorchid3", "magenta")) +
  scale_shape_manual(values=c(19, 17),
                     breaks = c("backshore sands", "intertidal sands"),
                     labels= c("Backshore", "Intertidal")) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(face="bold", size=12),
        axis.title.y = element_text(face="bold", size=12),
        axis.text.x = element_text(colour = "black", size=10),
        axis.text.y = element_text(colour = "black", size=10), 
        legend.title = element_text(size=13.5, face = "bold"),
        legend.text = element_text(size=13.5),
        legend.position="right")

##Plot
pca_plot2 = pca_plot + 
  geom_segment(mapping = pca_arrow_map, 
               size = 0.5, data = species.scores, 
               color = "black", arrow = pca_arrowhead) + 
  geom_text(mapping = pca_label_map, 
            size = 4, data = species.scores, 
            show.legend = FALSE) 

pca_plot2

Fig. S1

########################################################################################################
####Boxplot of Environmental varibales--------------Fig.S1
#########################################################################################################
sand2017_env3 = sand2017_env2 #Creat a duplicate ENV data.frame
sand2017_env3$Environment <- sand2017_env$Environment

##Reshape the data
sum_sand2017_env <- gather(sand2017_env3, "Env_factors", "Value",
                           Grain.size,  EC, TN, NH4.N, NO2.N,
                           NO3.N, Available.P, TOC, Pb, Cr,
                           As, Cu, Zn)

##Change Env_factors 
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors <- as.character(sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors)
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "Available.P"] <- "Available P (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "Grain.size"] <- "Grain size (D90, um)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "NH4.N"] <- "NH4-N (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "NO2.N"] <- "NO2-N (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "NO3.N"] <- "NO3-N (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "EC"] <- "EC (uS/cm)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "TN"] <- "TN (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "TOC"] <- "TOC (wt%)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "Pb"] <- "Pb (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "Cr"] <- "Cr (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "As"] <- "As (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "Cu"] <- "Cu (mg/kg)"
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors[sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors == "Zn"] <- "Zn (mg/kg)"

##Change other factors
sum_sand2017_env$Environment <- as.character(sum_sand2017_env$Environment)
sum_sand2017_env$Environment[sum_sand2017_env$Environment == "backshore sands"] <- "Supratidal"
sum_sand2017_env$Environment[sum_sand2017_env$Environment == "intertidal sands"] <- "Intertidal"

##set factor
sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors <-factor(sum_sand2017_env$Env_factors, 
                                      levels=c("Grain size (D90, um)", "EC (uS/cm)", "TN (mg/kg)",
                                               "NH4-N (mg/kg)", "NO2-N (mg/kg)", "NO3-N (mg/kg)",
                                               "Available P (mg/kg)",  "TOC (wt%)", "Pb (mg/kg)",
                                               "Cr (mg/kg)", "As (mg/kg)", "Cu (mg/kg)",
                                               "Zn (mg/kg)"))



##Plot
p_box_env1 = ggboxplot(sum_sand2017_env, x = "Environment", y = "Value",
          color = "Environment", palette = c("blue", "red"),
          add = "jitter", 
          facet.by = "Env_factors", scales = "free_y",
          short.panel.labs = T) +
  stat_compare_means(label =  "p.signif", label.x = 1.5, label.y.npc = 0.95, 
                     size = 4.5) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        axis.text.x = element_text(colour = "black", size=12.5, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(colour = "black", size=12),
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(face="bold", size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
        legend.title = element_text(size=10, face="bold"),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 10),
        strip.text = element_text(size = 12.5, face = "bold"),
        legend.position="none")

gen$Genus <- Genus

# The phyloseq object!
dongshan_sand.nonsing1 <- prune_taxa(taxa_sums(dongshan_sand.nonsing) > 0, dongshan_sand.nonsing) 
good_genus <-tax_glom(dongshan_sand.nonsing1, taxrank = "Genus")

##Fuzzy matching
list1 = agrep("uncultured", unique(gen$Genus), value=TRUE, max.dist=0.25) #### fuzzy matching 2
list2 = agrep("Ambiguous", unique(gen$Genus), value=TRUE, max.dist=0.25)
list3 = agrep("metagenome", unique(gen$Genus), value=TRUE, max.dist=0.25)
list4 = agrep("group", unique(gen$Genus), value=TRUE, max.dist=0.15)
list = c(list1, list2, list3, list4)

for (i in unique(list)) {
  good_genus %>%
    subset_taxa(Genus != i) -> good_genus

                   N = length(PercentAbund),
                   PercentPhy = mean(PercentAbund),
                   sd   = sd(PercentAbund),
                   se   = sd / sqrt(N))

###The beta-diversity null model analysis was performed by using the R code from Tucker et al., (2016)
betanull_bacwhole.out = read.table("bnullout_sand_whole.txt", header=TRUE, sep="\t")
betanull_bacgen.out = read.table("bnullout_sand_gen.txt", header=TRUE, sep="\t")
betanull_bacspe.out = read.table("bnullout_sand_spe.txt", header=TRUE, sep="\t")

betanull_bacwhole.out = merge(betanull_bacwhole.out[,c(1:2)], sand2017_env[,c(1,5,7)], 
                          by = 0, all = T)
betanull_bacgen.out = merge(betanull_bacgen.out[,c(1:2)], sand2017_env[,c(1,5,7)], 
                              by = 0, all = T)
betanull_bacspe.out = merge(betanull_bacspe.out[,c(1:2)], sand2017_env[,c(1,5,7)], 
                              by = 0, all = T)

betanull_bacwhole.out$group=paste("Whole")
betanull_bacgen.out$group=paste("Generalist")
betanull_bacspe.out$group=paste("Specialist")

###Kruskal-Wallis test
betanull_whole_KW <- kruskalmc(betanull_bacwhole.out$BRAY_AbundanceNullDeviation,
                                      betanull_bacwhole.out$Environment)
betanull_bacgen_KW <- kruskalmc(betanull_bacgen.out$BRAY_AbundanceNullDeviation,
                               betanull_bacgen.out$Environment)
betanull_bacspe_KW <- kruskalmc(betanull_bacspe.out$BRAY_AbundanceNullDeviation,
                                betanull_bacspe.out$Environment)


### Time to figure out letters to represent significance in a plot
whole_test <- betanull_whole_KW$dif.com$difference # select logical vector
names(whole_test) <- row.names(betanull_whole_KW$dif.com) # add comparison names
# create a list with "homogenous groups" coded by letter
whole_letters <- multcompLetters(whole_test, compare="<", threshold=0.05,
                                Letters=c(letters, LETTERS, "."), reversed = FALSE)

###  Extract the values from the multcompLetters object
whole_sigs_dataframe <-  data.frame(as.vector(names(whole_letters$Letters)), as.vector(whole_letters$Letters))
colnames(whole_sigs_dataframe) <- c("Environment", "siglabel")
betanull_bacwhole.out <- merge(betanull_bacwhole.out, whole_sigs_dataframe, by = "Environment")


### Time to figure out letters to represent significance in a plot
gen_test <- betanull_bacgen_KW$dif.com$difference # select logical vector
names(gen_test) <- row.names(betanull_bacgen_KW$dif.com) # add comparison names
# create a list with "homogenous groups" coded by letter
gen_letters <- multcompLetters(gen_test, compare="<", threshold=0.05,
                                 Letters=c(letters, LETTERS, "."), reversed = FALSE)

###  Extract the values from the multcompLetters object
gen_sigs_dataframe <-  data.frame(as.vector(names(gen_letters$Letters)), as.vector(gen_letters$Letters))
colnames(gen_sigs_dataframe) <- c("Environment", "siglabel")
betanull_bacgen.out <- merge(betanull_bacgen.out, gen_sigs_dataframe, by = "Environment")


### Time to figure out letters to represent significance in a plot
spe_test <- betanull_bacspe_KW$dif.com$difference # select logical vector
names(spe_test) <- row.names(betanull_bacspe_KW$dif.com) # add comparison names
# create a list with "homospeous groups" coded by letter
spe_letters <- multcompLetters(spe_test, compare="<", threshold=0.05,
                               Letters=c(letters, LETTERS, "."), reversed = FALSE)

###  Extract the values from the multcompLetters object
spe_sigs_dataframe <-  data.frame(as.vector(names(spe_letters$Letters)), as.vector(spe_letters$Letters))
colnames(spe_sigs_dataframe) <- c("Environment", "siglabel")
betanull_bacspe.out <- merge(betanull_bacspe.out, spe_sigs_dataframe, by = "Environment")

##Identify above, below and netural OTUs 
addf = function(freq, pred.upr, pred.lwr) {
  if(freq > pred.upr){
    model = "above"
  }
  else if(freq < pred.lwr){
    model = "below"
  }
  else if(pred.upr >= freq & freq >= pred.lwr){
    model = "neutral"
  }
  return(model)
}

mod1_w_back$model = mapply(addf, mod1_w_back$freq, mod1_w_back$pred.upr, mod1_w_back$pred.lwr)
